What is HTTP?
A request-response protocol — client always initiates, server only replies
After every response, the connection closes
HTTP/1.0 → 1 request = 1 connection (pure close after response)
HTTP/1.1 → Keep-Alive lets connection linger briefly for reuse, but still request-response
Server can never push data on its own — it waits to be asked

The problem with HTTP for real-time
You only see updated data (likes, messages, scores) when you refresh or revisit — because a new request is the only trigger
Polling (asking every few seconds) wastes millions of requests — most return empty
Long polling is smarter but still hacky — connection is reopened constantly

What is WebSocket?
A persistent, full-duplex connection — opened once, stays open
Both client and server can send messages at any time — no asking needed
Event-driven: something changes → the other side is notified instantly
No repeated HTTP headers — very low overhead per message

